net.hudup.core.data

Interface Fetcher<E>

  • Type Parameters:
    E - type of elements that the fetcher iterates over, which should be serializable.
    All Superinterfaces:
    AutoCloseable, java.rmi.Remote, java.io.Serializable, TextParsable
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    MemFetcher, MetaFetcher

    public interface Fetcher<E>
extends java.rmi.Remote, AutoCloseable, TextParsable, java.io.Serializable
    Fetcher is the interface for iterating each item of an associated collection. Fetcher is created by some classes. Following is an example of using fetcher.

    Fetcher<Object> fetcher = ...
    while(fetcher.next()) {
      Object element = fetcher.pick();
    }
    fetcher.close();
    Version:
    10.0
    Author:
    Loc Nguyen

      • close

        void close()
    throws java.rmi.RemoteException
        Closing this fetcher. After closed, fetcher cannot be reused. Fetcher has a mechanism of auto-closing because it extends AutoCloseable interface. This close() method is inherited from AutoCloseable interface. Concretely, if programmer forgets closing this fetcher after using, the finalize() will call this method to close this fetcher before the Java garbage collector destroys this fetcher.
        Specified by:
        close in interface AutoCloseable
        Throws:
        java.rmi.RemoteException - if any remote exception raises.
